{"title_page": "Almacenes T\u00eda", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=T\u00eda|2=Talk:Almacenes T\u00eda#Requested move 6 March 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{Infobox company\n| name          = T\u00eda S.A.\n| image         =\n| image_caption = Storefront of a Tia supermarket in Ecuador\n| type          = [[Private company]]\n| foundation    = 1940, [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]]\n| founder       = Federico Deutsch, Karel Steuer\n| location      = [[Ecuador]], [[Uruguay]]\n| industry      = [[Retail]]\n| area_served   = [[Ecuador]], [[Uruguay]]\n| divisions     = T\u00eda S.A. (Ecuador) <br> MAGDA Supermercados S.A (Ecuador) <br> Ta-Ta S.A. (Uruguay) <br> Multi Ahorro S.A. (Uruguay)\n| homepage      = {{URL|www.tia.com.ec}} - Tia Ecuador\n}}\n\n'''Tiendas Industriales Asociadas S.A.''', branded as '''T\u00eda''' and sometimes known as '''Almacenes T\u00eda''',<ref>{{cite news|title=Almacenes T\u00eda abre nuevo local|trans-title=Almacenes T\u00eda opens new store|date=September 7, 2019|accessdate=March 7, 2020|url=https://www.lahora.com.ec/santodomingo/noticia/1102270911/almacenes-tia-abre-nuevo-local|newspaper=[[La Hora]]|language=es}}</ref> is a [[South American]] retailing brand founded in 1940. Its divisions in [[Ecuador]] and [[Uruguay]]  trade under the brands T\u00eda, MAGDA, Ta-Ta and MULTI AHORRO, where they are together the largest [[discount retailer]], with over 450 locations. T\u00eda S.A. (Colombia) operated 19 locations under the T\u00eda brand, until it closed in 2017 because of poor sales.\n\n== History ==\nT\u00eda was formed by the [[Eastern European]] [[supermarket chain]] Te-Ta founded by Kerel Steuer and Federico Deutsch in the 1920s in [[Prague]]. They traded in Czechoslovakia, [[Yugoslavia]] and [[Romania]], but in 1940, after the start of World War II, they emigrated to the Americas, leaving everything behind. They restarted that year in [[Bogot\u00e1]], Colombia as '''T\u00eda''', and later expanded into Argentina, Peru, Uruguay and Ecuador using T\u00eda and other brand names.\n\nSteuer and Deutsch had stores where customers could find everything, with no need to shop elsewhere. The first T\u00eda store in South America  on October 14, 1940, on [[Carrera S\u00e9ptima]] in Bogot\u00e1.\n\nThe South American store industry has been a support for the development of this business organization, which besides the supermarket segment, allowed small manufacturing operations to arise over time and become important manufacturing companies in Colombia, Argentina, Ecuador, and Uruguay. T\u00eda was one of the first stores to enter the market of private labels. This store was a pioneer in many aspects, which have served as a basis for national and international chains to modernize their business model.\n\nCurrently, T\u00eda is present in Ecuador and Uruguay. The Argentinean division with its 61 stores was sold to French supermarket chain [[Carrefour]] in 1999 for US$630 million and was rebranded first as Norte, then as Carrefour. The Peruvian division was sold after failing in the Peruvian market. The Colombian division closed in 2017 after 77 years.\n\nT\u00eda is majority-owned by [[Francisco de Narv\u00e1ez]] and family, Gustavo Andr\u00e9s Deutsch, and financial institutions.\n\n== Formats ==\nT\u00eda trades as:<ref name=empresa>{{cite web |url=https://www.tia.com.ec/empresa.asp |title=Definici\u00f3n de negocio |language=Spanish |publisher=T\u00eda |access-date=2011-11-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111121190246/http://www.tia.com.ec/empresa.asp |archive-date=2011-11-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n* '''T\u00eda''': Supermarkets are located in cities with populations over 25,000.\n* '''Super T\u00eda''': Hypermarkets are located in cities with populations over 125,000.\n* '''Plaza T\u00eda''': Shopping malls with a T\u00eda supermarket and a variety of complementary stores.\n* '''T\u00eda Express''': A small supermarket format.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tia.com.ec/noticias.asp |title=Noticias Tia |access-date=2011-11-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125180619/http://www.tia.com.ec/noticias.asp |archive-date=2011-11-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* '''MULTI AHORRO''': Neighborhood supermarkets in [[Barrio]]s, bought in 2012 by T\u00eda's Uruguayan branch Ta-Ta.\n* '''MAGDA Supermercados''': An Ecuadorian supermarket chain bought in 2012.\n* '''''Ta-Ta''''': The brand name for T\u00eda in Uruguay.<ref>[http://web.tata.com.uy/uc_13_1.html TaTa]{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111228154035/http://web.tata.com.uy/uc_13_1.html |date=2011-12-28 }}.</ref>\n* '''Tarjeta M\u00e1s''': An credit card operation on Ecuador.\n\n===Websites===\n*Ecuador {{official website|https://www.tia.com.ec/index.asp}}\n* Uruguay {{official website|https://www.multiahorro.com.uy/index.asp}}\n\n== Locations ==\n=== Colombia ===\nThe first store opened in Bogot\u00e1 on October 14, 1940, on [[Carrera S\u00e9ptima]]. Their business model was new to Colombia.<ref name=websiteTia>{{official website|https://www.tia.com.ec/index.asp}}</ref>\n\nT\u00eda had supermarkets in Bogot\u00e1, [[Medell\u00edn]], [[Bucaramanga]], [[Barranquilla]], [[C\u00facuta]], [[Sogamoso]], [[Ibagu\u00e9]], [[Facatativ\u00e1]], [[Palmira, Valle del Cauca|Palmira]], and [[Tunja]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tia.com.co/ciudad.html |title=T\u00eda in Colombia |access-date=2011-11-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110905130513/http://www.tia.com.co/ciudad.html |archive-date=2011-09-05 |url-status=dead |df= }}{{primary source-inline|date=March 2020}}</ref>\necided to\nT\u00eda Colombia closed its doors on November 23, 2017 after 77 years of trading, because of its continual losses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elespectador.com/economia/fin-de-una-era-almacenes-tia-cerrara-sus-tiendas-en-el-pais-articulo-724737|title=End of an Era, T\u00eda will close its stores in Colombia|language=Spanish |publisher=El Espectador}}</ref>\n\n===Argentina ===\nThe first store opened  Buenos Aires in 1946. An innovative business concept was to put round island shelves in each department.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.elargentino.com/nota-14073-El-cuento-de-la-(Casa)-Tia.html |title=El cuento de la casa Tia |access-date=2011-11-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929035759/http://www.elargentino.com/nota-14073-El-cuento-de-la-(Casa)-Tia.html |archive-date=2011-09-29 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> In 1999, Exxel, a buyout fund backed by American investors, and [[Promodes]], France's then second-largest retail chain, bought T\u00eda's Argentine division and its 61 stores for $630 million. Carrefour (after acquiring Promodes) spent another $600 million over three years to add stores.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.entrepreneur.com/tradejournals/article/54470640.html |title=Exxel still shopping |journal=[[Entrepreneur (magazine)|Entrepreneur]] |issue=May 1999}}</ref>\n\nTwo of the founders' descendants, brothers Carlos and [[Francisco de Narv\u00e1ez]], wanted to reopen T\u00eda in Argentina. In 2009 they bought back the Argentine brand from [[Carrefour]] and promised to re-establish the supermarket chain's Argentine division, starting in Buenos Aires.<ref>[http://www.ieco.clarin.com/empresas/Vuelve-Casa-Tia-antiguos-duenos_0_575942463.html Vuelve Casa Tia - antiguos due\u00f1os]</ref>\n\n=== {{anchor|Ta-Ta Uruguay}}Uruguay === <!-- Courtesy comment per [[MOS:LINK2SECT]]. Redirect [[Ta-Ta]] links here. -->\nOn June 13, 1956, T\u00eda's subsidiary Ta-Ta opened the first department store in Uruguay at the corner of [[18 de Julio Avenue]] and Carlos Roxlo, kicking off modernization of the retail and supermarket industry in Uruguay.\n\nIn 2012 Ta-Ta bought the Uruguayan supermarket and electronic department store chain '''Multi Ahorro'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historico.elpais.com.uy/121123/ultmo-677478/ultimomomento/ta-ta-compro-la-red-multi-ahorro/|title=Ta-Ta compr\u00f3 la red Multi-Ahorro|language=es}}</ref>\n\nTa-Ta employs more than 6000 employees, and has hypermarkets located in all 19 of the country's departments. As of March 2012, Ta-Ta was the biggest retailer in Uruguay with over 30% market share.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://web.tata.com.uy/uc_13_1.html |title=T\u00eda Uruguay |access-date=2011-11-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111228154035/http://web.tata.com.uy/uc_13_1.html |archive-date=2011-12-28 |url-status=dead |df= }}{{primary source-inline|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Ecuador ===\nThe first store in Ecuador opened in the downtown of [[Guayaquil]] on November 29, 1960. In 2017, T\u00eda was the biggest retailer, and eleventh in the ranking of the best companies in Ecuador.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rp3.com.ec/almacenes-tia-continua-creciendo-actualmente-cuenta-con-mas-de-180-tiendas-y-7-500-empleados/|title=Almacenes T\u00eda keeps growing with now having more than 180 stores y 7.500 employees.|language=Spanish |publisher=RP3 Retail Software}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111127151907/http://www.tia.com.ec/index.asp Tia Ecuador]\n* [http://www.multiahorro.com.uy Multi Ahorro Uruguay]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111130235359/http://web.tata.com.uy/ Ta-Ta Uruguay]\n* [http://www.tia.com.co Tia Colombia]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tia}}\n[[Category:Supermarkets of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Companies of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Supermarkets of Uruguay]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1940]]\n[[Category:1940 establishments in Colombia]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=T\u00eda|2=Talk:Almacenes T\u00eda#Requested move 6 March 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{Infobox company\n| name          = T\u00eda S.A.\n| image         =\n| image_caption = Storefront of a Tia supermarket in Ecuador\n| type          = [[Private company]]\n| foundation    = 1940, [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]]\n| founder       = Federico Deutsch, Karel Steuer\n| location      = [[Ecuador]], [[Uruguay]]\n| industry      = [[Retail]]\n| area_served   = [[Ecuador]], [[Uruguay]]\n| divisions     = T\u00eda S.A. (Ecuador) <br> MAGDA Supermercados S.A (Ecuador) <br> Ta-Ta S.A. (Uruguay) <br> Multi Ahorro S.A. (Uruguay)\n| homepage      = {{URL|www.tia.com.ec}} - Tia Ecuador\n}}\n\n'''Tiendas Industriales Asociadas S.A.''', branded as '''T\u00eda''' and sometimes known as '''Almacenes T\u00eda''',<ref>{{cite news|title=Almacenes T\u00eda abre nuevo local|trans-title=Almacenes T\u00eda opens new store|date=September 7, 2019|accessdate=March 7, 2020|url=https://www.lahora.com.ec/santodomingo/noticia/1102270911/almacenes-tia-abre-nuevo-local|newspaper=[[La Hora]]|language=es}}</ref> is a [[South American]] retailing brand founded in 1940. Its divisions in [[Ecuador]] and [[Uruguay]]  trade under the brands T\u00eda, MAGDA, Ta-Ta and MULTI AHORRO, where they are together the largest [[discount retailer]], with over 450 locations. T\u00eda S.A. (Colombia) operated 19 locations under the T\u00eda brand, until it closed in 2017 because of poor sales.\n\n== History ==\nT\u00eda was formed by the [[Eastern European]] [[supermarket chain]] Te-Ta founded by Kerel Steuer and Federico Deutsch in the 1920s in [[Prague]]. They traded in Czechoslovakia, [[Yugoslavia]] and [[Romania]], but in 1940, after the start of World War II, they emigrated to the Americas, leaving everything behind. They restarted that year in [[Bogot\u00e1]], Colombia as '''T\u00eda''', and later expanded into Argentina, Peru, Uruguay and Ecuador using T\u00eda and other brand names.\n\nSteuer and Deutsch had stores where customers could find everything, with no need to shop elsewhere. The first T\u00eda store in South America  on October 14, 1940, on [[Carrera S\u00e9ptima]] in Bogot\u00e1.\n\nThe South American store industry has been a support for the development of this business organization, which besides the supermarket segment, allowed small manufacturing operations to arise over time and become important manufacturing companies in Colombia, Argentina, Ecuador, and Uruguay. T\u00eda was one of the first stores to enter the market of private labels. This store was a pioneer in many aspects, which have served as a basis for national and international chains to modernize their business model.\n\nCurrently, T\u00eda is present in Ecuador and Uruguay. The Argentinean division with its 61 stores was sold to French supermarket chain [[Carrefour]] in 1999 for US$630 million and was rebranded first as Norte, then as Carrefour. The Peruvian division was sold after failing in the Peruvian market. The Colombian division closed in 2017 after 77 years.\n\nT\u00eda is majority-owned by [[Francisco de Narv\u00e1ez]] and family, Gustavo Andr\u00e9s Deutsch, and financial institutions.\n\n== Formats ==\nT\u00eda trades as:<ref name=empresa>{{cite web |url=https://www.tia.com.ec/empresa.asp |title=Definici\u00f3n de negocio |language=Spanish |publisher=T\u00eda |access-date=2011-11-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111121190246/http://www.tia.com.ec/empresa.asp |archive-date=2011-11-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n* '''T\u00eda''': Supermarkets are located in cities with populations over 25,000.\n* '''Super T\u00eda''': Hypermarkets are located in cities with populations over 125,000.\n* '''Plaza T\u00eda''': Shopping malls with a T\u00eda supermarket and a variety of complementary stores.\n* '''T\u00eda Express''': A small supermarket format.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tia.com.ec/noticias.asp |title=Noticias Tia |access-date=2011-11-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125180619/http://www.tia.com.ec/noticias.asp |archive-date=2011-11-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* '''MULTI AHORRO''': Neighborhood supermarkets in [[Barrio]]s, bought in 2012 by T\u00eda's Uruguayan branch Ta-Ta.\n* '''MAGDA Supermercados''': An Ecuadorian supermarket chain bought in 2012.\n* '''''Ta-Ta''''': The brand name for T\u00eda in Uruguay.<ref>[http://web.tata.com.uy/