{"title_page": "2016 South Korean legislative election", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2016 South Korean legislative election\n| country            = South Korea\n| type               = parliamentary\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = 2012 South Korean legislative election\n| previous_year      = 2012\n| next_election      = 2020 South Korean legislative election\n| next_year          = 2020\n| seats_for_election = All 300 seats of the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]]\n<br /> 151 seats were needed for a majority\n| turnout            = 58.0% ({{increase}}3.8 [[Percentage point|pp]])\n| outgoing_members   = [[List of members of the National Assembly (South Korea), 2012\u20132016|Outgoing members]]\n| elected_mps        = [[List of members of the National Assembly (South Korea), 2016\u20132020|Incoming members]]\n| election_date      = 13 April 2016\n| image1             = [[File:Kim Jongin's press conference in 2016 (cropped to Kim).jpg|125px]]\n| leader1            = [[Kim Chong-in]]\n| leader_since1      = 27 January 2016\n| party1             = [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic]]\n| color1             = 0052A7\n| last_election1     = {{Nowrap|127 seats}}<br />{{small|(as [[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2011)|DUP]])}}\n| leaders_seat1      = [[Party-list proportional representation|PR List]] 2\n| seats_before1      = 102\n| seats1             = '''123'''\n| seat_change1       = {{increase}} 21\n| popular_vote1      = 6,069,744\n| percentage1        = 25.5%\n| swing1             = {{decrease}} 11.0% \n| image2             = [[File:Kim_Moo-sung_State.jpg|125px]]\n| leader2            = [[Kim Moo-sung]]\n| leader_since2      = 14 July 2014\n| leaders_seat2      = [[Busan]]&nbsp;[[Jung District, Busan|Jung]]\u2013[[Yeongdo District|Yeongdo]]\n| party2             = [[Liberty Korea Party|Saenuri]]\n| color2             = C9151E\n| last_election2     = {{nowrap|152 seats}}<br />([[Advancement Unification Party|LFP]]: 5 seats)\n| seats_before2      = 146\n| seats2             = 122\n| seat_change2       = {{decrease}} 24\n| popular_vote2      = '''7,960,272'''\n| percentage2        = '''33.5%'''\n| swing2             = {{decrease}} 12.5%\n| image4             = [[File:Ahn Cheol-Soo cropped (cropped).jpg|125px]]\n| leader4            = [[Ahn Cheol-soo]]<br />[[Chun Jung-bae]]\n| leader_since4      = 2 February 2016\n| leaders_seat4      = [[Seoul]]&nbsp;[[Nowon District|Nowon]]&nbsp;C<br />[[Gwangju]]&nbsp;[[Seo District, Gwangju|Seo]]&nbsp;B\n| party4             = [[People's Party (South Korea, 2016)|People's]]\n| color4             = 006241\n| last_election4     = ''New party''\n| seats_before4      = 20\n| seats4             = 38\n| seat_change4       = {{increase}} 18\n| popular_vote4      = 6,355,572\n| percentage4        = 26.7%\n| swing4             = ''New party''\n| image5             = [[File:Sim Sang-jung.jpg|125px]]\n| leader5            = [[Sim Sang-jung]]\n| leader_since5      = 18 July 2015\n| leaders_seat5      = [[Gyeonggi]]&nbsp;[[Goyang]]&nbsp;A\n| party5             = [[Justice Party (South Korea)|Justice]]\n| color5             = FFCC00\n| last_election5     = ''New party''\n| seats_before5      = 5\n| seats5             = 6\n| seat_change5       = {{increase}} 1\n| popular_vote5      = 1,719,891\n| percentage5        = 7.2%\n| swing5             = ''New party''\n| title              = Speaker\n| before_election    = [[Chung Ui-hwa]]\n| before_party       = Saenuri Party\n| posttitle          = \n| after_election     = [[Chung Sye-kyun]]\n| after_party        = Democratic Party of Korea\n| map                = Popular vote totals given are direct votes for the parties' national lists. <br /> [[File:2016 20\ub300 \ucd1d\uc120 \uc9c0\uc5ed\uad6c.svg|350px]]\n|note = \n}}\n{{Politics of South Korea}}\n\n'''South Korea's 20th legislative elections''' were held on 13 April 2016. All 300 members of the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]] were elected, 253 from [[first-past-the-post]] [[_South Korean Legislature Constituencies|constituencies]] and 47 from [[party-list proportional representation|proportional party lists]]. The election was an upset victory for the liberal [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]], which defied opinion polling by winning a plurality of seats in the election and defeating the ruling conservative [[Liberty Korea Party|Saenuri Party]] by one seat. In votes for party lists, however, [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]] came third, behind the Saenuri Party in first place and the new [[People's Party (South Korea, 2016)|People's Party]] in second.\n\nThe election marked an upheaval in the South Korean party system, installing a [[hung parliament]] for the first time since [[2000 South Korean legislative election|2000]] and a [[multi-party system|three-party system]] for the first time since [[1996 South Korean legislative election|1996]].<ref name=\"KoreaHerald3rdParty\">{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160413000614|title=Minority People's Party steals show: Ahn's Party holds balance of power as three party system dawns|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=13 April 2016|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> The People's Party attained a kingmaker position in the new Assembly, while the leadership of the Saenuri Party including chairman [[Kim Moo-sung]] resigned en masse following their defeat, relinquishing control of the party to an emergency response commission.\n\nThe 2016 legislative election was the first to be held in South Korea following the formation of the People's Party and the enforcement of controversial [[Constitutional Court of Korea|Constitutional Court]] rulings dissolving the left-wing [[Unified Progressive Party]] and mandating the redistricting of the Assembly's constituencies.\n\n==Background==\nIn the [[2012 South Korean legislative election|2012 legislative election]], the ruling conservative [[Liberty Korea Party|Saenuri Party]] won a slim majority of 152 seats out of 300.<ref name=\"Herald 16/4/9\">{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160110000398|title=Can Saenuri Party take 180 seats?|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=10 January 2016|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> The party also retained control of the presidency, as Saenuri candidate [[Park Geun-hye]] won the [[2012 South Korean presidential election|presidential election that year]]. By the time of the 2016 legislative election, the Saenuri delegation had fallen to 146 out of 292 filled Assembly seats, exactly 50%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2016/03/30/0200000000AEN20160330011800315.html|title=Parliamentary candidates launch official campaigning|publisher=[[Yonhap News]]|date=31 March 2016|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> The 2016 election was seen as an important stepping stone to the [[2017 South Korean presidential election|2017 presidential election]], which was held on May 9, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/s-korea-ruling-party-set-to-regain-majority|title=South Korea's ruling party set to regain majority|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|date=9 April 2016|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Redistricting===\nIn 2014, the [[Constitutional Court of Korea]] mandated that because the population disparities between the Assembly constituencies were resulting in unequal representation, the constituencies must be redistricted for the 2016 elections. The Court held that [[Apportionment (politics)|the largest and smallest constituencies by population]] must not differ from each other by more than 2:1, and that the number of constituents in any given constituency must not differ from the average number of constituents by more than one third.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccourt.go.kr/home/iframe/storybookinfo_view05.jsp?eventNo=2012%C7%E5%B8%B6192&mainseq=146&seq=5&sch_date=&sch_time=&eventnum=&board_id=&comm_id=&media_id=a&accident1=2012&accident2=%C7%E5%B8%B6&accident3=192&accident_name=&law_name=&provision=&regname=&flag=1&pg=1|title=\uacf5\uc9c1\uc120\uac70\ubc95\uc81c25\uc870 \uc81c2\ud56d \ubcc4\ud45c1\uc704\ud5cc\ud655\uc778|language=Korean|work=Constitutional Court of Korea|date=30 October 2014|accessdate=16 May 2015|trans-title=Civil Election Law Article 25 Section 2 Asterisk 1 Decided Unconstitutional}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nA deadline of 31 December 2015 was set for the redistricting to take place. Nonetheless, by the end of 2015 the National Assembly had not approved a new electoral map. Viewing the situation as an emergency, the National Election Commission was forced to allow registered candidates to campaign without a set map of constituencies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3013388&ref=mobile|title=NEC allows campaigning without new electoral map|newspaper=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=31 December 2015|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> The crisis was ultimately resolved in February 2016 with an agreement between the two major parties that allowed a new electoral map to be passed by the National Assembly. The new set of provisions raised the number of districts from 246 to 253, while decreasing the number of list-selected seats from 54 to 47.<ref name=\"districts\">{{cite news|last=Kim|first=Hyo-jin|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/02/116_198780.html|title=Parties agree on electoral map|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=23 February 2016|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: \"\n|+\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align: center;\" |Region\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" |Number of seats changed\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align: center;\" |Region\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" |Number of seats changed\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align: center;\" |Region\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" |Number of seats changed\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[Seoul]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |48 \u2192 49 \n| style=\"text-align: center;background:lightpink;\" |'''+1'''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[Ulsan]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |6 \u2192 6 \n| style=\"text-align: center;\"|'''0'''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[South Jeolla]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |11 \u2192 10 \n| style=\"text-align: center;background:skyblue;\"|'''\u22121'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[Busan]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |18 \u2192 18 \n| style=\"text-align: center;\"|'''0'''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[Gyeonggi]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |52 \u2192 60 \n| style=\"text-align: center;background:pink;\"|'''+8'''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[North Gyeongsang]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |15 \u2192 13 \n| style=\"text-align: center;background:skyblue;\"|'''\u22122'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[Daegu]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |12 \u2192 12 \n| style=\"text-align: center;\"|'''0'''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[Gangwon Province (South Korea)|Gangwon]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |9 \u2192 8 \n| style=\"text-align: center;background:skyblue;\"|'''\u22121'''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[South Gyeongsang]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |16 \u2192 16\n| style=\"text-align: center;\"|'''0'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[Incheon]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |12 \u2192 13 \n| style=\"text-align: center;background:lightpink;\" |'''+1'''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | [[North Chungcheong]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |8 \u2192 8\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''0'''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[Jeju Province|Jeju]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |3 \u2192 3\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''0'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[Gwangju]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |8 \u2192 8 \n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''0'''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[South Chungcheong]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |10 \u2192 11\n| style=\"text-align: center;background:lightpink;\" |'''+1'''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[Sejong City|Sejong]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |1 \u2192 1\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''0'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | [[Daejeon]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |6 \u2192 7\n| style=\"text-align: center;background:lightpink;\" |'''+1'''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[North Jeolla]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |11 \u2192 10\n| style=\"text-align: center;background:skyblue;\" |'''\u22121'''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |[[Proportional representation]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |54 \u2192 47\n| style=\"text-align: center;background:skyblue;\" |'''\u22127'''\n|}\n\n===Reordering of the opposition===\nIn the aftermath of the [[2013 South Korean sabotage plot]], another controversial Constitutional Court ruling enforced the dissolution of the [[Unified Progressive Party]] due to the party's alleged ideological affinity to [[North Korea]]. The dissolution of the UPP left the [[Justice Party (South Korea)|Justice Party]] as the sole left-wing democratic socialist party in the National Assembly. The [[Korean Confederation of Trade Unions]], the most influential democratic trade union organisation in Korea that had originally supported the UPP, now endorsed the Justice Party. The Justice Party's candidates and Assembly members were considered to have similar political views as the left-wing members of the main opposition [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]], and many votes from the Justice Party shifted to the Democratic Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2015/02/18/2015021800214.html|title=[19\ub300 \uad6d\ud68c \uc774\ub150\ubd84\uc11d] \u8207\u91ce \uc774\ub150 \uac04\uadf9, \uae40\ubb34\uc131\u00b7\ubb38\uc7ac\uc778(\uc5ec\uc57c \ub2f9 \ub300\ud45c) \uba40\uace0 \uc720\uc2b9\ubbfc\u00b7\uc6b0\uc724\uadfc(\uc5ec\uc57c \uc6d0\ub0b4 \ub300\ud45c) \uac00\uae4c\uc6cc|language=Korean|work=Chosun Ilbo|date=18 February 2015|accessdate=16 May 2015|trans-title=[19th Assembly Ideology Breakdown] Majority-Minority Ideological divide, Kim Moo-sung, Moon Jae-in (Party leaders) far Yoo Seong-min, Woo Yoon-geun (Assembly leaders) close}}</ref>\n\nThe opposition was further fragmented when [[Ahn Cheol-soo]] defected from the main opposition Democratic Party and established a new [[People's Party (South Korea, 2016)|People's Party]] in early 2016. Due to South Korea's largely [[first-past-the-post]] electoral system, the division between the liberal Democratic and People's parties had led to projections of a sweeping victory for the ruling Saenuri Party in the elections.<ref name=\"Herald 16/4/9\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://thediplomat.com/2016/04/history-repeats-in-south-koreas-crumbling-opposition-party/|title=History Repeats in South Korea's Crumbling Opposition: At the center of controversy is fallen rebel Ahn Cheol-soo.|last=Ramirez|first=Elaine|newspaper=[[The Diplomat]]|date=5 April 2016|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> The two opposition parties considered an electoral alliance but by April 5 the idea was abandoned, with interim Democratic leader [[Kim Chong-in]] stating that his party \"will hold the elections whether the People\u2019s Party is there or not\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=3017151|title=Minjoo, People's Party abandon alliance idea|newspaper=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=6 April 2016|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Legislative gridlock===\nThe outgoing 19th National Assembly was marked by [[political gridlock]]. In February 2016, Democratic lawmakers undertook the world's longest filibuster to stall an anti-terrorism bill, and the Assembly passed less than a third of the bills introduced in its term. The Saenuri Party aimed to win a supermajority of 180 seats in the 2016 election so that it could ease the gridlock by repealing the existing requirement for three-fifths of the Assembly to agree to the introduction of each bill.<ref name=\"economist\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21696545-south-koreans-are-fed-up-politicians-squabbling-no-walk-park|title=No walk in the Park: South Koreans are fed up with politicians squabbling|magazine=[[The Economist]]|date=9 April 2016|accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral system==\n{{see also|Elections in South Korea}}\n300 members of the National Assembly were elected in the 2016 elections, of whom 253 (84%) were elected from single-member constituencies on a first-past-the-post basis, and 47 (16%) from [[closed list|closed party lists]] through [[Party-list proportional representation|proportional representation]] by the [[largest remainder method|Hare quota largest remainder method]], in accordance with South Korea's Public Official Election Act.<ref name=\"districts\" /><ref>Article 189, subsection (3), Public Official Election Act, {{cite web|url=http://www.nec.go.kr/engvote_2013/05_resourcecenter/02_01.jsp|title=Legislation & Judicial Decision|publisher=Republic of Korea National Election Commission|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> In order to win seats through proportional representation, parties needed to pass an [[election threshold]] of either 5 single-member districts or 3% of the total list vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nec.go.kr/engvote_2013/02_elections/01_04.jsp|title=Election Districts and Representation System|publisher=Republic of Korea National Election Commission|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Restrictions on candidates===\nCandidates for the National Assembly were required to pay a fee of {{Currency|amount=15000000|type=KRW|first=yes}} (US$13,000 as of April 2016), and under the [[National Security Act (South Korea)|National Security Act]] the Constitutional Court may block the registration of \"left-wing\", \"pro\u2013North Korean\" parties, though this provision had not affected the previous election in 2012.<ref name=\"SGI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sgi-network.org/2015/South_Korea/Quality_of_Democracy|title=South Korea|publisher=[[Sustainable Governance Indicators]]|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Date and process===\nThe 2016 election for the National Assembly was held on April 13, in accordance with Article 34 of the Public Official Election Act, which specifies that Election Day for legislative elections is held on \"the first Wednesday from the 50th day before the expiration of the [National Assembly members'] term of office\".<ref>Article 34, Public Official Election Act, {{cite web|url=http://www.nec.go.kr/engvote_2013/05_resourcecenter/02_01.jsp|title=Legislation & Judicial Decision|publisher=Republic of Korea National Election Commission|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> Eligible voters were required to be registered and at least 19 years old on the day of the election,<ref name=\"SGI\" /> and needed to show an approved form of identification at the [[polling place]]. Polls on Election Day were open from 6 a.m. to 6 p.m. [[Korea Standard Time]] (21:00\u201309:00 UTC, April 12\u201313).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nec.go.kr/engvote_2013/04_news/04_01_voting.jsp|title=National Assembly elections: April 13, 2016|publisher=Republic of Korea National Election Commission|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nSince 2009, voters have been able to vote overseas,<ref name=\"SGI\" /> and the election began with registered overseas voters casting ballots between March 30 and April 4.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2016/03/28/2016032801386.html|title=Korean Expats to Cast Early Votes in General Elections|newspaper=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|date=28 March 2016|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> For the first time in a national election, the National Election Commission also allowed early votes to be cast at polling stations in Korea without notice.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lee|first=Rachel|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/04/116_202228.html|title=Early voting begins for general election|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=8 April 2016|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> This early voting period lasted from April 8 to 9,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160327000405|title=Korea readies for election with advanced balloting system|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=27 March 2016|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> in which time the NEC reported a high turnout of 12.2%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2016/04/09/0200000000AEN20160409000552315.html|title=S. Korea records highest voter turnout of early voting|publisher=[[Yonhap News]]|date=9 April 2016|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Parties and candidates==\n{{see also|List of political parties in South Korea}}\nFour major parties contested the 2016 election:<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mediatoday.co.kr/?mod=news&act=articleView&idxno=129314|title=\uc0c8\ub204\ub9ac\ub2f9\uacfc \uac70\ub9ac, \uad6d\ubbfc\uc758\ub2f9-\ub354\ubbfc\uc8fc-\uc815\uc758\ub2f9 \uc21c|publisher=Media Today|trans-title=Distant from Saenuri Party, People's Party\u2013Minjoo Party\u2013Justice Party in order|date=12 April 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016|language=ko}}</ref>\n* The [[Liberty Korea Party|Saenuri Party]], led by [[Kim Moo-sung]], the [[conservatism in South Korea|conservative]] ruling party<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160412000831|title=Feud-Plagued parties go to polls|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=12 April 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n* The [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]], led on an interim basis by Kim Chong-in, the main [[liberalism in South Korea|liberal]] opposition party<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://thediplomat.com/2016/03/can-a-right-wing-defector-save-koreas-liberal-opposition/|title=Can a Right Wing Defector Save Korea's Liberal Opposition?|magazine=[[The Diplomat]]|date=22 March 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n* The [[People's Party (South Korea, 2016)|People's Party]], led jointly by Ahn Cheol-soo and [[Chun Jung-bae]], a centrist party formed in early 2016 from a split from the Democratic Party<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160307000793|title=Ahn's party feuds over opposition unity|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=7 March 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n* The [[Justice Party (South Korea)|Justice Party]], led by standing chairwoman [[Sim Sang-jung]], a left-wing progressive party<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20150721000879|title=Future of progressives: New Justice Party leader faces many challenges|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=21 July 2015|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nTwo other parties had one member in the outgoing National Assembly: the religious conservative [[Christian Liberal Party]],<ref name=\"KoreaHeraldReligion\">{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160411001013|title=Religion-affiliated parties want to 'protect' country from Islam, homosexuality|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=11 April 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> and another center-left party known as the [[Minjoo Party (2014)|Minjoo Party]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.donga.com/3/all/20160317/77062178/2|title=\uc2e0\uae30\ub0a8 \uc6d0\uc678 \ubbfc\uc8fc\ub2f9 \uc785\ub2f9\u202618\uc77c \uc785\ub2f9 \uae30\uc790\ud68c\uacac \uac1c\ucd5c|language=ko|newspaper=[[Donga Ilbo]]|date=March 17, 2016|accessdate=March 27, 2016}}</ref><ref group=\"n\">Unless otherwise specified, \"Minjoo\" or \"Minjoo Party\" refers to the main opposition Democratic Party of Korea, not the minor party.</ref>\n\n===Candidate nominations===\nThe Saenuri Party's candidate nomination process proved contentious. Several members of the Saenuri nominations committee accused party chairman [[Kim Moo-sung]] of becoming unduly involved in the process, and the party [[deselection|deselected]] a number of candidates who were seen as being opposed to the party leadership and President Park Geun-hye.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/03/116_200677.html|title=Saenuri nominations stalled|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=18 March 2016|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> Many of the deselected candidates defected from the party and announced that they would run as independents. On April 4, a spokesman for the party said that \"during the candidate selection process, we upset our people and [the number of] our supporters who may not vote is worse [than we expected].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.voanews.com/content/trump-north-korea-could-help-conservatives-in-south-korea-election/3269684.html|title=Trump, North Korea Could Help Conservatives in South Korean Election|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|date=5 April 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> The party published a theme song apologizing for the nominations controversy.<ref name=\"KoreaTimes\" /> It also is thought by many that it was the main reason that caused the Saenuri Party to lose.\n\n==Campaign==\nCampaigning for the election officially began on March 30, lasting until April 12. Under South Korean law, candidates were only permitted to campaign in a limited fashion before the beginning of the designated period, including sending a maximum of five text messages publicizing themselves to each voter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160324000913|title=Parties enter campaign mode|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=24 March 2016|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===National security issues===\nNational security issues were a topic of contention in the campaign between the Saenuri and Democratic parties, though the People's Party focused on other policy areas.<ref name=\"HankyorehSecurity\" />\n\nThe Saenuri Party argued for a hard-line approach to North Korea, and Saenuri chairman Kim Moo-sung accused the main opposition Democratic Party of pro\u2013North Korean activity due to its support for the reopening of the [[Kaesong Industrial Complex]],<ref name=\"KoreaTimes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/04/180_202361.html|title=Policy competition disappears in election campaign|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=12 April 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> an industrial park operated collaboratively by North and South Korea that had been closed down in February 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/feb/10/seoul-shuts-down-joint-north-south-korea-industrial-complex-kaesong|last=McCurry|first=Justin|title=Seoul shuts down joint North-South Korea industrial complex |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=10 February 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> The Democratic Party sought to portray the reopening of the complex as an economic rather than a political issue.<ref name=\"HankyorehSecurity\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_national/738992.html|title=[Analysis] Parties' unification, security and foreign affairs platforms for general elections|newspaper=[[The Hankyoreh]]|date=10 April 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe South Korean government announced a series of defections from the North in early April, with critics viewing the announcements as an electoral strategy on behalf of the ruling party.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/04/116_202368.html|title=N. Korean intelligence colonel fled to the South |newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=11 April 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> A local media report quoted an unnamed government official as saying that the [[Blue House]] had overruled the [[Ministry of Unification]]'s objections to publicizing the defections.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/04/485_202314.html|title=Cheong Wa Dae accused of votes bid over N. Korean defectors |newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=11 April 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> The Ministry of Unification denied any connection between the announcements and the election campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2016/04/seoul-denies-political-aspect-of-revealing-n-koreans-defection/|title=Seoul denies political timing in revealing N.Koreans' defections|publisher=[[NK News]]|date=11 April 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nCandidates from both the opposition and the ruling party also pledged to push for the relocation of U.S. military bases from their constituencies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/04/116_202292.html|title=Election pledges to move military bases trigger concerns|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=10 April 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Economic issues===\nThe Korean economy was a dominant area of debate,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-36031147|title=South Korea elections: Saenuri party looks to strengthen position|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=13 April 2016|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> as the governing Saenuri Party promoted business-friendly economic reforms while opposition parties attacked the government for presiding over a historically high youth unemployment rate and declining economic growth.<ref name=\"VOA\">{{cite news|url=http://www.voanews.com/content/south-korean-election-could-reinforce-status-quo/3283563.html|title=South Korean Election Could Reinforce Status Quo|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|date=13 April 2016|accessdate=13 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414131702/http://www.voanews.com/content/south-korean-election-could-reinforce-status-quo/3283563.html|archive-date=14 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Saenuri Party sought to gain support for labor reforms initiated by President Park, which aimed to cut unemployment by increasing contract flexibility. Trade unions attacked the plans, arguing that the new laws would strip away necessary protections from workers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-04-10/korean-election-brings-park-s-labor-law-overhaul-to-a-crossroad|title=Korean Election Brings Park's Labor-Law Overhaul to a Crossroad|publisher=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]|date=10 April 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> The Democratic Party accused the ruling party of economic mismanagement,<ref name=\"KoreaHeraldVotes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160411000882|title=Parties make last-ditch pleas for votes|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=11 April 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> and used the campaign to push for \"[[economic democracy|economic democratization]]\" and a shift from larger conglomerates to small business;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://asia.nikkei.com/Viewpoints/Viewpoints/Peter-S.-Kim-Will-South-Korea-choose-long-term-economic-reform-or-band-aid-solutions?page=2|title=Will South Korea choose long-term economic reform or band-aid solutions?|last=Kim|first=Peter S.|newspaper=[[Nikkei Asian Review]]|date=7 April 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> the party also promised to raise pensions and the minimum wage, to sponsor public housing development,<ref name=\"VOA\" /> and to expand mandatory youth employment quotas.<ref name=\"HeraldWelfare\">{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160411000885|title=Parties lack pragmatic plans for welfare|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=11 April 2016|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> Critics argued that Democratic plans would have a distortionary effect on the labor market.<ref name=\"HeraldWelfare\" /> Sim Sang-jung, chairwoman of the left-wing Justice Party, argued that the Saenuri, Democratic, and People's parties had all failed to articulate distinctive economic policies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160403000385|title=Parties blame each other for weak economy|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=3 April 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Social issues===\nSpeaking in Seoul during the campaign, Saenuri chairman Kim Moo-sung described homosexuality as \"an outrage against humanity\",<ref name=\"KoreaHeraldVotes\" /> urging voters to reject candidates who supported LGBTQ rights.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.kr/2016/04/09/story_n_9648708.html|title=\uae40\ubb34\uc131, \"\ub3d9\uc131\uc560 \ucc2c\uc131 \ud6c4\ubcf4\ub294 \ub9c9\uc544\uc57c \ud55c\ub2e4\"|trans-title=Kim Moo-sung: \"Candidates supporting homosexuality must be stopped\"|newspaper=[[The Huffington Post|The Huffington Post Korea]]|date=9 April 2016|accessdate=12 April 2016|language=ko}}</ref> He described Democratic assemblywoman [[Nam In-soon]] as a pro-gay advocate for supporting the revision of a military criminal law in 2013 to include men as well as women as potential victims of sexual assault.<ref name=\"KoreaHeraldVotes\" /> The Christian Liberal Party also rallied vociferously against LGBTQ rights and stoked Islamophobia, calling on voters to \"protect our families from homosexuality and Islam\".<ref name=\"KoreaHeraldReligion\" />\n\n==Opinion polls==\n[[File:Opinion polling for the 2016 South Korean legislative election.png|thumb|450px|right|Graph of selected opinion polls for the 2016 legislative election, beginning at the end of 2015 with the first polls accounting for the new People's Party. The moving average is calculated from the last three polls.\n {{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n {{Legend-line|#C00000 solid 5px|Saenuri}}\n {{Legend-line|#2E75B6 solid 5px|Democratic}}\n {{Legend-line|#385723 solid 5px|People's}}\n {{Legend-line|#FFC000 solid 5px|Justice}}\n }}\n ({{Legend0|#D2D1D3}} Poll embargo period)\n]]\nOpinion polls from prior to the election had suggested the Saenuri Party would win the election outright, and were confounded by Saenuri underperformance in constituencies and the comparative success of the Democratic and People's parties.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160414000872|title=Pre-election surveys' credibility questioned|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=18 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/south-korea-ruling-party-expected-to-fall-short-of-parliament-majority-exit-polls-show-1460545395|title=Election Delivers Setback to South Korean Leader|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=13 April 2016|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> The [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]] exit poll on April 13 showed the Saenuri Party winning a plurality with between 121 and 143 seats, and the Democratic Party taking 101\u2013123; other exit polls projected similar results.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-36033773|title=South Korea elections: President Park's party 'loses majority'|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=13 April 2016|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> South Korean law had prohibited the publication of opinion polls in the week before the elections, beginning on April 7.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2016/04/06/2016040602325.html|title=7\uc77c\ubd80\ud130 \ucd1d\uc120 \uc5ec\ub860\uc870\uc0ac \uacb0\uacfc \uacf5\ud45c \uae08\uc9c0|trans-title=Opinion poll result publication banned from the 7th|newspaper=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|date=6 April 2016|accessdate=10 April 2016|language=ko}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:85%; line-height:16px; margin:0;\"\n|- style=\"height:42px; background-color:#E9E9E9; border 1px solid #aaaaaa;\"\n! style=\"width:160px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Date\n! style=\"width:160px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Polling firm\n! style=\"width:40px;\" class=\"unsortable\"| [[Liberty Korea Party|Saenuri]]\n! style=\"width:40px;\" class=\"unsortable\"| [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic]]<ref group=\"n\">Known as the New Politics Alliance for Democracy until 28 December 2015.</ref>\n! style=\"width:40px;\" class=\"unsortable\"| [[People's Party (South Korea, 2016)|People's]]\n! style=\"width:40px;\" class=\"unsortable\"| [[Justice Party (South Korea)|Justice]]\n! style=\"width:40px;\" rowspan=\"2\" class=\"unsortable\"| Oth.\n! style=\"width:20px;\" rowspan=\"2\" class=\"unsortable\"| Lead\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Saenuri Party/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{Democratic Party of Korea/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{People's Party (South Korea, 2016)/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{Justice Party (South Korea)/meta/color}}\"|\n|- class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF; font-weight:bold;\"\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-04-13\"|13 Apr 2016\n| Election ({{abbr|PR|Proportional representation}})\n|{{Party shading/Saenuri Party}}| 33.5\n| 25.5\n| 26.7\n| 7.2\n| 6.9\n|style=\"background:{{Saenuri Party/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| 8.0\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-04-07\"|5\u20137 Apr 2016\n|[https://archive.today/20160409135129/http://news.naver.com/main/election/news/read.nhn?mode=LSD&oid=469&aid=0000136988&cid=1040322&iid=24689123 Hankook Research]\n|{{Party shading/Saenuri Party}}| '''28.4'''\n| 21.7\n| 16.9\n| 4.4\n| 5.1\n|style=\"background:{{Saenuri Party/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| 6.7\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-04-06\"|4\u20136 Apr 2016\n|[http://www.gallup.co.kr/gallupdb/reportContent.asp?seqNo=740 Gallup Korea]\n|{{Party shading/Saenuri Party}}| '''39'''\n| 21\n| 14\n| 5\n| \u2013\n|style=\"background:{{Saenuri Party/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| 18\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-04-06\"|4\u20136 Apr 2016\n|[http://www.realmeter.net/2016/04/%EC%B4%9D%EC%84%A0-d-6-%EC%97%84%EC%82%B4-%EC%9E%91%EC%A0%84-%EC%83%88%EB%88%84%EB%A6%AC%EB%8B%B9-%ED%95%98%EB%9D%BD%EC%84%B8-%EC%A7%80%EC%86%8D/ Realmeter]\n|{{Party shading/Saenuri Party}}| '''34.4'''\n| 27.3\n| 16.8\n| 8.3\n| 4.4\n|style=\"background:{{Saenuri Party/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| 7.1\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-04-01\"|28 Mar \u2013 1 Apr 2016\n|[http://www.realmeter.ne