ri Party}} | '''28.6%'''\n| 0\n| 28.5%\n| 0\n| 26.6%\n| 0\n| 8.9%\n| 0\n| 7.4%\n| style=\"background-color: #dedede;\" | '''1'''\n! 1\n|-\n! style=\"text-align: left;\" | [[Gyeonggi]]\n| 19\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''32.3%'''\n| {{party shading/Democratic Party of Korea}} | '''40'''\n| 26.8%\n| 0\n| 27.0%\n| 1\n| 7.8%\n| 0\n| 6.1%\n| 0\n! 60\n|-\n! style=\"text-align: left;\" | [[Gangwon Province (South Korea)|Gangwon]]\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''6'''\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''43.4%'''\n| 1\n| 23.9%\n| 0\n| 19.3%\n| 0\n| 5.7%\n| 0\n| 7.7%\n| 1\n! 8\n|-\n! style=\"text-align: left;\" data-sort-value=\"Chungcheong N\" | [[North Chungcheong]]\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''5'''\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''38.6%'''\n| 3\n| 27.6%\n| 0\n| 21.4%\n| 0\n| 5.6%\n| 0\n| 6.8%\n| 0\n! 8\n|-\n! style=\"text-align: left;\" data-sort-value=\"Chungcheong S\" | [[South Chungcheong]]\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''6'''\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''37.0%'''\n| 5\n| 27.1%\n| 0\n| 22.5%\n| 0\n| 5.6%\n| 0\n| 7.8%\n| 0\n! 11\n|-\n! style=\"text-align: left;\" data-sort-value=\"Jeolla N\" | [[North Jeolla]]\n| 1\n| 7.6%\n| 2\n| 32.3%\n| {{party shading/People's Party (South Korea)}} | '''7'''\n| {{party shading/People's Party (South Korea)}} | '''42.8%'''\n| 0\n| 8.1%\n| 0\n| 9.2%\n| 0\n! 10\n|-\n! style=\"text-align: left;\" data-sort-value=\"Jeolla S\" | [[South Jeolla]]\n| 1\n| 5.7%\n| 1\n| 30.0%\n| {{party shading/People's Party (South Korea)}} | '''8'''\n| {{party shading/People's Party (South Korea)}} | '''47.8%'''\n| 0\n| 5.8%\n| 0\n| 10.7%\n| 0\n! 10\n|-\n! style=\"text-align: left;\" data-sort-value=\"Gyeongsang N\" | [[North Gyeongsang]]\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''13'''\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''58.1%'''\n| 0\n| 12.9%\n| 0\n| 14.8%\n| 0 \n| 5.2%\n| 0\n| 9.0%\n| 0\n! 13\n|-\n! style=\"text-align: left;\" data-sort-value=\"Gyeongsang S\" | [[South Gyeongsang]]\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''12'''\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''44.0%'''\n| 3\n| 24.4%\n| 0\n| 17.4%\n| 1\n| 6.5%\n| 0\n| 7.7%\n| 0\n! 16\n|-\n! style=\"text-align: left;\" | [[Jeju Province|Jeju]]\n| 0\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''35.0%'''\n| {{party shading/Democratic Party of Korea}} | '''3'''\n| 29.6%\n| 0\n| 22.4%\n| 0\n| 7.0%\n| 0\n| 6.0%\n| 0\n! 3\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align: left;\" | [[_South Korean Legislature Constituencies|Constituency]] total\n!colspan=\"2\"| 105\n!colspan=\"2\"| 110\n!colspan=\"2\"| 25\n!colspan=\"2\"| 2\n!colspan=\"2\"| 0\n! 11\n! 253\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align: left;\" | [[Party-list proportional representation|PR list]]\n! 17\n! 33.5%\n! 13\n! 25.5%\n! 13\n! 26.7%\n! 4\n! 7.2%\n! 0\n! 7.0%\n| {{n/a}}\n! 47\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align: left;\" | Overall total\n!colspan=\"2\"| 122\n!colspan=\"2\"| 123\n!colspan=\"2\"| 38\n!colspan=\"2\"| 6\n!colspan=\"2\"| 0\n! 11\n! 300\n|}\n\n;Maps of regional party-list vote by party performance\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"220px\" style=\"text-align:left\">\nFile:Proportional representatives of legislative election 2016 Minjoo.svg|Democratic\nFile:Proportional representatives of legislative election 2016 Saenuri.svg|Saenuri\nFile:Proportional representatives of legislative election 2016 People.svg|People's\nFile:Proportional representatives of legislative election 2016 Justice.svg|Justice\n</gallery>\n\n==Aftermath==\n\nThe day after the election, Saenuri chairman Kim Moo-sung tendered his resignation over his party's defeat, saying that he would \"take responsibility for the resounding defeat in the general elections\"; [[Kim Tae-ho (politician)|Kim Tae-ho]], a member of the party's Supreme Council, and secretary-general [[Hwang Jin-ha]] also announced their resignation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160414000285|title=Saenuri Party leader Kim Moo-sung offers to step down over election debacle|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> After the mass resignation of the party leadership, the party established an emergency committee led by floor leader [[Won Yoo-chul]] to lead the party on an interim basis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160414000869|title=Ruling party reeling from election rout: Saenuri to launch emergency leadership, take in defectors|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=April 14, 2016|accessdate=April 14, 2016}}</ref> In order to regain the party's plurality in the Assembly, Won announced that Saenuri would receive independent lawmakers who had previously been deselected by the party back into its ranks. [[Ahn Sang-soo (born May 1946)|Ahn Sang-soo]], one of the deselected candidates who had re-entered the Assembly as an independent, declared his desire to rejoin the party, while another, [[Yoo Seong-min]], stated that he would rejoin at an appropriate time.<ref name=\"JoongAngIndependents\" />\n \nPresident Park stated on April 18 that she \"humbly accepted\" the election result, and would \"closely cooperate with the new National Assembly\".<ref name=\"herald2016-04-18\">{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160418000869|title=President accepts Saenuri defeat as people's message|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=18 April 2016|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/04/116_202869.html|title=Park and Saenuri's approval ratings dip to new lows|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=18 April 2016|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref> A survey conducted in the two days following the election showed Park's approval rating falling to 31.5 percent, her lowest ratings in office yet and 8.1 percentage points down from the week before the election.<ref name=\"herald2016-04-18\" />\n\nThe election was seen to have a limited effect on the Korean stock market, since the prospect of a hung parliament appeared to diminish the chance of ambitious economic policies being implemented.<ref name=\"KoreaHeraldStocks\">{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160414000801|title=Changed political landscape to have limited effect on stock market: analysts|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> Nonetheless, on a more limited scale, the performance of companies tied to prominent figures reflected the election results: shares in [[AhnLab Inc|AhnLab, Inc.]], whose founder and largest stakeholder is People's Party co-chairman Ahn Cheol-soo, had risen 5.2% by 2 p.m. KST on April 14 following Ahn's election success, while textile company Chonbang, chaired by Kim Moo-sung's brother, fell 19.2% in the same time frame.<ref name=\"KoreaHeraldStocks\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of members of the National Assembly (South Korea), 2016\u20132020]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{South Korean elections}}\n{{National Assembly (South Korea)|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Legislative elections in South Korea]]\n[[Category:2016 elections in Asia]]\n[[Category:2016 in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Election and referendum articles with incomplete results|2016]]\n[[Category:April 2016 events in Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2016 South Korean legislative election\n| country            = South Korea\n| type               = parliamentary\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = 2012 South Korean legislative election\n| previous_year      = 2012\n| next_election      = 2020 South Korean legislative election\n| next_year          = 2020\n| seats_for_election = All 300 seats of the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]]\n<br /> 151 seats were needed for a majority\n| turnout            = 58.0% ({{increase}}3.8 [[Percentage point|pp]])\n| outgoing_members   = [[List of members of the Nat