%EC%A0%84%EC%9C%BC%EB%A1%9C-%ED%9A%8C%EA%B7%80-%E6%96%87%C2%B7%EB%8D%94%EB%AF%BC%EC%A3%BC-%E9%87%91%C2%B7%EC%83%88%EB%88%84%EB%A6%AC-%EB%8F%99%EB%B0%98-%EC%83%81%EC%8A%B9/ Realmeter]\n|{{Party shading/Saenuri}}| '''39.2'''\n| 25.0\n| 17.1\n| 4.6\n| 3.9\n|style=\"background:{{Saenuri Party/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| 14.2\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-01-21\"|19\u201321 Jan 2016\n|[http://www.gallup.co.kr/gallupdb/reportContent.asp?seqNo=722 Gallup Korea]\n|{{Party shading/Saenuri}}| '''38'''\n| 19\n| 13\n| 3\n| \u2013\n|style=\"background:{{Saenuri Party/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| 19\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-01-15\"|11\u201315 Jan 2016\n|[http://www.realmeter.net/2016/01/%EC%9D%B8%EC%9E%AC%EC%98%81%EC%9E%85-%EA%B2%BD%EC%9F%81-%EC%86%8D-%E6%96%87-%EB%B0%98%EB%93%B1-vs-%E5%AE%89%C2%B7%E9%87%91-%EC%86%8C%ED%8F%AD-%ED%95%98%EB%9D%BD/ Realmeter]\n|{{Party shading/Saenuri}}| '''36.1'''\n| 22.5\n| 20.7\n| 3.7\n| 4.8\n|style=\"background:{{Saenuri Party/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| 13.6\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-01-08\"|4\u20138 Jan 2016\n|[http://www.realmeter.net/2016/01/%E5%8C%97%E9%A2%A8%EC%9C%BC%EB%A1%9C-%E6%9C%B4%EB%8C%80%ED%86%B5%EB%A0%B9-%EB%B0%98%EB%93%B1-%E5%AE%89%E9%A2%A8%EC%9C%BC%EB%A1%9C-%E9%87%91%C2%B7%E5%AE%89%C2%B7%E6%96%87-%EC%B4%88%EB%B0%95%EB%B9%99/ Realmeter]\n|{{Party shading/Saenuri}}| '''36.1'''\n| 20.3\n| 18.7\n| 3.8\n| 5.8\n|style=\"background:{{Saenuri Party/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| 15.8\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2015-12-31\"|28\u201331 Dec 2015\n|[http://www.realmeter.net/2016/01/%EC%9C%84%EC%95%88%EB%B6%80-%ED%95%A9%EC%9D%98-%EB%85%BC%EB%9E%80-%EB%8C%80%ED%86%B5%EB%A0%B9-%EB%B6%80%EC%A0%95%ED%8F%89%EA%B0%80-4%EC%A3%BC-%EC%97%B0%EC%86%8D-%EC%83%81%EC%8A%B9/ Realmeter]\n|{{Party shading/Saenuri}}| '''35.2'''\n| 23.6\n| 17.3<ref group=\"n\" name=\"Ahn\">Speculative support for \"Ahn Cheol-soo's new party\".</ref>\n| 5.8\n| 5.0\n|style=\"background:{{Saenuri Party/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| 11.6\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2015-12-24\"|21\u201324 Dec 2015\n|[http://www.realmeter.net/2015/12/%E5%AE%89-%ED%83%88%EB%8B%B9-%ED%9B%84%ED%8F%AD%ED%92%8D-%E6%96%87-%EF%A4%8A-%E5%AE%89-%EC%98%A4%EC%B0%A8%EB%B2%94%EC%9C%84-%EB%82%B4-%EC%B4%88%EC%A0%91%EC%A0%84/ Realmeter]\n|{{Party shading/Saenuri}}| '''37.2'''\n| 22.4\n| 19.0<ref group=\"n\" name=\"Ahn\" />\n| 6.1\n| 3.0\n|style=\"background:{{Saenuri Party/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| 14.8\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n|colspan=14|\n|- style=\"background:#EFEFEF; font-weight:bold;\" class=\"sortbottom\"\n| 11 Apr 2012\n| [[2012 South Korean legislative election|Last election]] ({{abbr|PR|Proportional representation}})\n|{{Party shading/Saenuri}}| 42.8\n| 36.5<ref group=\"n\">[[Democratic United Party]] result.</ref>\n| \u2013\n| 10.3<ref group=\"n\">[[Unified Progressive Party]] result.</ref>\n| 12.9\n|style=\"background:{{Saenuri Party/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| 6.3\n|}\n;General notes\n* Gallup Korea provides poll results only to the nearest whole number.\n\n==Results==\n\n[[File:Korean ballots box.jpg|thumb|Sealed ballot box used for this election]]\nPrior to the election, it was widely expected that the Saenuri Party would emerge victorious due to divisions in the opposition and an intensified national security climate.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/south-koreans-polls-parliamentary-election-38348849|title=South Korean President's Party Suffers Election Setback|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> Speculation had focused on whether the party would be able to attain a three-fifths majority.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160110000398|title=Can Saenuri Party take 180 seats?|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=12 January 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> In contrast to expectations, however, the Saenuri Party was delivered a decisive defeat, losing not only its majority but also its status as largest party in the Assembly.<ref name=\"JoongAngResult\">{{cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3017526|title=Saenuri routed, Democratic becomes the first, Ahn gains clout|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> The Democratic Party took a one-seat plurality, and the opposition outnumbered the governing party for the first time in 16 years,<ref name=\"KoreaHerald3rdParty\" /> while the centrist People's Party also emerged as a new force in South Korean politics, holding the balance of power in the elected Assembly.<ref name=\"KoreaHerald3rdParty\" /> The result was seen as posing significant problems for then-President Park,<ref name=\"JoongAngResult\" /> who was rendered unable to press forward with her legislative agenda without opposition support.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.japantoday.com/category/world/view/economic-woes-threats-from-north-overshadow-s-korean-legislative-elections|title=Economic woes, threats from North overshadow S Korean legislative elections|publisher=[[Japan Today]]|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> News sources labelled Park a \"[[lame duck (politics)|lame duck]]\" president,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/conservative-rout-leaves-south-koreas-park-geunhye-a-lame-duck/news-story/16ca1208ddd42854cf92dae327574176?nk=c07dd96332972d39c73e50067a02b460-1460645891|title=Conservative rout leaves South Korea's Park Geun-hye a lame duck|newspaper=[[The Australian]]|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> with the ''[[Chosun Ilbo]]'' saying that her \"lame duck period has started earlier than any other administration in the past\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-southkorea-election-idUSKCN0XA2LC|title=Vote defeat for South Korea's Park raises 'lame duck' prospect|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nEleven independents were elected, of whom seven were former Saenuri members who had been deselected by the party in the nominations process prior to the election: [[Yoo Seong-min]], [[Joo Ho-young]], [[Ahn Sang-soo (born May 1946)|Ahn Sang-soo]], [[Yoon Sang-hyun (politician)|Yoon Sang-hyun]], [[Kang Ghil-boo]], [[Chang Je-won]], and [[Lee Chul-gyu]].<ref name=\"JoongAngIndependents\">{{cite news|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3017605|title=Saenuri begs victorious independents to return|newspaper=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=16 April 2016|accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref> Meanwhile, a number of high-profile Saenuri figures were defeated in the constituency elections, including [[Oh Se-hoon]], former [[Mayor of Seoul]], who had been positioning himself for the 2017 presidential race; senior lawmaker and former presidential candidate [[Lee Jae-oh]]; and [[Deputy Prime Minister of South Korea|Deputy Prime Minister]] and former party chairman [[Hwang Woo-yea]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160414000429|title=Parliamentary election result to realign rival parties|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Summary of results===\n{| style=\"width:70%;\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2193\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Justice Party (South Korea)/meta/color}}; text-align:center; width:2%;\"|'''6'''</span>\n| style=\"background:{{Minjoo Party of Korea/meta/color}}; text-align:center; width:41%;\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">'''123'''</span>\n| style=\"background:{{People's Party (South Korea)/meta/color}}; text-align:center; width:12.7%;\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">'''38'''</span>\n| style=\"background:#aaaaaa; text-align:center; width:3.7%;\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">'''11'''</span>\n| style=\"background:{{Saenuri Party/meta/color}}; text-align:center; width:40.7%;\"|<span style=\"color:white;\">'''122'''</span>\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top;\" | <span style=\"color:#FFAE00;\">'''Justice'''</span>\n| style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top;\" | <span style=\"color:{{Minjoo Party of Korea/meta/color}};\">'''Democratic'''</span>\n| style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top;\" | <span style=\"color:{{People's Party (South Korea)/meta/color}};\">'''People's'''</span>\n| style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top;\" | <span style=\"color:#aaaaaa;\">'''Ind.'''</span>\n| style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top;\" | <span style=\"color:{{Saenuri Party/meta/color}};\">'''Saenuri'''</span>\n|}\n\n[[File:South Korean Legislative Election 2016.svg|thumb|right|275px|Diagram of the elected 20th National Assembly]]\n{{Pie chart\n| thumb = right\n| caption = Diagram of party-list vote\n| other = \n| label1 =Saenuri Party\n| value1 =33.50\n| color1 ={{Saenuri Party/meta/color}}\n| label2 =People's Party\n| value2 =26.75\n| color2 ={{People's Party (South Korea)/meta/color}}\n| label3 =Democratic Party\n| value3 =25.55\n| color3 ={{Minjoo Party of Korea/meta/color}}\n| label4 =Justice Party\n| value4 =7.24\n| color4 ={{Justice Party (South Korea)/meta/color}} \n| label5 =Other parties\n| value5 =6.97\n| color5 =#aaaaaa\n}}\n{{South Korean legislative election, 2016}}\n\n===Results by region===\n\nThe table below lists constituency totals and list vote percentages in each region. Since the election was run under a [[parallel voting]] system, electors could choose to vote for one party in their constituencies while voting for another party's national list. Exit polls indicated that 12.9% of those who had voted for the Saenuri Party in their constituencies and 20.8% of those for the Democratic Party supported the People's Party list.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_editorial/739893.html|title=People's Party opens the way to a real three party system|newspaper=[[The Hankyoreh]]|date=15 April 2016|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size: 0.9em;\"\n|+Constituency and party list results by region<ref>{{cite web|url=http://psephos.adam-carr.net/countries/k/korea/korea20161.txt|title=REPUBLIC OF KOREA LEGISLATIVE ELECTION OF 13 APRIL 2016|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Adam Carr|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=16 June 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" | Region \n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:40px;\" class=\"unsortable\"| [[Liberty Korea Party|Saenuri]]\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:40px;\" class=\"unsortable\"| [[Minjoo Party of Korea|Democratic]]\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:40px;\" class=\"unsortable\"| [[People's Party (South Korea, 2016)|People's]]\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:40px;\" class=\"unsortable\"| [[Justice Party (South Korea)|Justice]]\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:40px;\" class=\"unsortable\"| Other\n! style=\"width:40px;\" class=\"unsortable\"| [[Independent (politician)|Ind.]]\n! rowspan=\"3\" | Total<br />seats\n|-\n! Seats\n! Vote %\n! Seats\n! Vote %\n! Seats\n! Vote %\n! Seats\n! Vote %\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Seats\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Vote %\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Seats\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:{{Saenuri Party/meta/color}};\"|\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:{{Minjoo Party of Korea/meta/color}};\"|\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:{{People's Party (South Korea, 2016)/meta/color}};\"|\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:{{Justice Party (South Korea)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n! style=\"text-align: left;\" | [[Seoul]]\n| 12\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''30.8%'''\n| {{party shading/Minjoo Party of Korea}} | '''35'''\n| 25.9%\n| 2\n| 28.8%\n| 0\n| 8.5%\n| 0\n| 6.0%\n| 0\n! 49\n|-\n! style=\"text-align: left;\" | [[Busan]]\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''12'''\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''41.2%'''\n| 5\n| 26.6%\n| 0\n| 20.3%\n| 0\n| 6.0%\n| 0\n| 5.9%\n| 1\n! 18\n|-\n! style=\"text-align: left;\" | [[Incheon]]\n| 4\n| {{party shading/Saenuri Party}} | '''33.4%'''\n| {{party shading/Minjoo Party of Korea}} | '''7'''\n| 25.4%\n| 0\n| 26.9%\n| 0\n| 7.5%\n| 0\n| 